1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
For 3.5 million community health workers,
medicine begins here.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:14,000
Aïcha is a community health worker.

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Today, she sees Mariam.
14 months old. Fever. Lethargic.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Her guide: a 200-page paper protocol.
And zero network.

5
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:36,000
A bad triage decision:
1 child dies preventably every minute. — WHO

6
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Aïcha needs a doctor. Now.
But the doctor is 80 km away.

7
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:53,000
This is MediBoussole.

8
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:00,000
100% offline. No data
ever leaves the phone.

9
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:08,000
She speaks her own language.
Wolof, Bambara, Fula, French — it doesn't matter.

10
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:18,000
One photo. Gemma 4 sees
what Aïcha sees.

11
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Gemma 4 E4B —
native multimodal, on-device.

12
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:38,000
RAG: every answer is grounded
in WHO protocols.

13
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Red triage. Criteria: high fever,
lethargy, moderate dehydration.

14
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:58,000
Gemma 4 function calling:
SMS auto-generated.

15
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:08,000
The SMS goes out via 2G.
No internet required.

16
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Twenty minutes later. Mariam is on her way.
The doctor is already waiting.

17
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:25,000
The doctor receives a structured
clinical summary. She already knows.

18
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:38,000
3.5 million CHWs.
A €150 Android phone. Zero internet required.

19
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:50,000
MediBoussole doesn't replace Aïcha.
It amplifies her.

20
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:00,000
MediBoussole · Built on Gemma 4 + Ollama
Open source · CC-BY 4.0
